The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Tuesday, December 14, 2004 

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, Dec. 13: Wednesday?s bus strike was today deferred till December 31. 

 Sadhan Das, general secretary of the Joint Council of Bus Syndicates, which called the strike, said: ?We put it off following transport minister Subhas Chakraborty?s request.? The syndicate, an association of bus owners, is demanding a fare hike in the wake of the rise in fuel prices. 

 Calcutta: An exercise to fill up principals? posts in 84 colleges ended on Monday, but half the institutions will continue to be headless. The college service commission has found only 42 candidates suitable. Announcing the results of the selection tests, its chairman Ajit Kumar Banik said: ?Those deserving are not ready to go to the rural belts.? There was no application at all for 14 colleges. For the job, teachers should put in 15 continuous years and have a doctorate degree. 

 Behrampore: The central food-for-work scheme was initiated in Murshidabad on Monday. It is one of 150 districts chosen by the Union government for the project.




